>). Compare   Center  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Center","meanings":["English and Scottish (Aberdeenshire): metonymic occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>ceinture</i>, <i>seinture</i> ‘girdle’, denoting someone who made or sold girdles, or perhaps a nickname for someone who wore a distinctive girdle.","English: variant of   Senter   1.","Americanized form of German   Zehnder   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Sant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Krishan, Anagha, Anjali, Arvind, Deepak, Milind, Nilima, Ravindra, Sanjeev, Sanjiv, Vasudev.","English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Saint  .","Italian (northeastern): variant of   Santo  ."]},{"name":"Sante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Luc, Camille, Lucien.  Spanish Alejandro, Anselmo, Carlos, Emilio, Jesusa, Jorge.","French (also <b>Santé</b>): probably a nickname for a healthy person, from French <i>santé</i> ‘good health’.","Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Spanish (southwestern): habitational name from one of several places called Sante, in Galicia, Portugal, and Asturias, from a Visigothic personal name. This surname is also found in the Philippines."]}]},{"name":"Amand","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Walloon, and in some cases possibly also English (of Norman origin), Dutch, or Flemish: from the Old French personal name <i>Amand</i>, <i>Amant</i>, Latin <i>amandus</i> ‘suitable to be loved’, the name of a 5th-century bishop of Bordeaux and several other Christian saints. In England it was also used as a female personal name."],"variants":[{"name":"Ament","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Amand  .","German: variant of   Amend  .","Hungarian (<b>Áment</b>): probably of German origin (see 2 above). The surname <i>Ament</i>, presumably of Hungarian origin, is also found in Croatia."]}]},{"name":"Almaric","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Germanic personal name composed of <i>ala</i> ‘all’ or <i>ali</i> ‘stranger’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. Now rare, it was introduced to Britain in this form by the Normans. The first element may also in part derive from a contracted form of <i>adal</i> ‘noble’. The Blessed Alaricus or Adalricus (  d. 975 ) was a Swabian prince who became a monk at the monastery of Einsiedeln in Switzerland."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":41,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Third Baron Almaric de Saint Amand was born in 1341, in Wiltshire, England. He married Alianore Laventon 2 wife. He died on 13 June 1402, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1341–13 June 1402":"1341–13. juuni 1402","1360–1426":"1360–1426","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1395–1416":"1395–1416","1341–1402":"1341–1402","1426":"1426","1402":"1402","1345":"1345","13 June 1402":"13. juuni 1402","1341":"1341","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1416":"1416","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Hornchurch, Essex, England":"Hornchurch, Essex, England"},"fi":{"1341–13 June 1402":"1341–13. kesäkuuta 1402","1360–1426":"1360–1426","1345–Female":"1345–Kuollut","1395–1416":"1395–1416","1341–1402":"1341–1402","1426":"1426","1402":"1402","1345":"1345","13 June 1402":"13. kesäkuuta 1402","1341":"1341","1395":"1395","138